00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:05.400
decided to build a remote
controlled garbage can.

00:08:05.400 --> 00:08:08.650
I mean, how lazy is that?

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:13.210
And I remember I built this
little model of a trash can,

00:08:13.210 --> 00:08:15.910
and it was a tiny
little replica,

00:08:15.910 --> 00:08:18.370
and on the day of the
science fair, I took it in,

00:08:18.370 --> 00:08:21.040
and the science fair
was held in our gym.

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:24.580
And I remember I just spent the
day piloting this little trash

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:26.690
can around other
people's projects

00:08:26.690 --> 00:08:29.511
instead of actually
presenting it.

00:08:29.511 --> 00:08:31.080
And these were fun times.

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:32.669
They were fun projects.

00:08:32.669 --> 00:08:33.840
Everyone was laughing.

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:37.350
It was a lot of fun, but
I wasn't really asking

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:42.270
the types of questions that
could change the world.

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:47.310
In fact, I really didn't ask the
important scientific questions

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:50.640
until I turned 15
years old, and then I

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:53.220
became-- I went
from this kid who

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:56.590
was doing silly science
projects to a kid who

00:08:56.590 --> 00:08:59.240
wanted to cure cancer.

00:08:59.240 --> 00:09:02.480
When I was 15, my
grandfather passed away.

00:09:02.480 --> 00:09:07.340
My grandfather was one of
the most organized people

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:09.240
I've ever met.

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:13.430
He was the kind of person who
would save hundreds of horribly

00:09:13.430 --> 00:09:16.060
taken pictures from
family road trips that

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:19.200
were blurry and awful, and he
would label them and keep them

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:21.260
in photo albums for years.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:23.990
And he had these
file cabinets that

00:09:23.990 --> 00:09:26.915
were just full of
chronologically ordered

00:09:26.915 --> 00:09:31.580
"National Geographic" magazines
that were 30 years old,

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:37.000
but that wasn't the man I saw
towards the end of his life.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.340
My grandfather had
become bedridden.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:41.890
He was dependent.

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:47.110
He wasn't the same grandfather
I had grown up with,

00:09:47.110 --> 00:09:48.680
and that was hard.

00:09:48.680 --> 00:09:51.590
That was really hard to
see, and he wasn't alone

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:52.940
in that experience.

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:56.460
I mean, a lot of people
all over the world

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:58.720
are affected by cancer--
maybe some of you

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:01.620
guys, maybe some of
your family members.

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:05.320
I mean, by the numbers,
there are millions,

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:08.910
but usually it just
takes one to really want

00:10:08.910 --> 00:10:10.620
to make a difference.

00:10:10.620 --> 00:10:14.600
And for me, my
grandfather was my one,

00:10:14.600 --> 00:10:18.510
and I knew I had
to do something.

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:23.330
So what do you do when you have
a lot of big questions and very

00:10:23.330 --> 00:10:25.080
few answers?

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:29.950
Well, I did what any 15-year-old
would do, and I googled it.

00:10:29.950 --> 00:10:33.790
I started reading everything
I could get my hands on.

00:10:33.790 --> 00:10:36.300
I read scientific articles.

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:39.520
I read blog posts
from cancer patients

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:41.690
who were going
through chemotherapy.

00:10:41.690 --> 00:10:45.160
I even read some
pretty nutty conspiracy

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:49.780
theories about cancer,
and I remember I learned.

00:10:49.780 --> 00:10:50.930
I learned a lot.

00:10:50.930 --> 00:10:54.550
I was learning every
day, and I would

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:56.796
go to-- I would learn
outside of class,

00:10:56.796 --> 00:10:58.420
and then I would go
into the classroom,

00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:01.910
and we would see these diagrams
of how cancer supposedly

00:11:01.910 --> 00:11:03.090
happened.

00:11:03.090 --> 00:11:06.090
And I remember one
day sitting in class,

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:09.820
seeing this diagram
of this piece of DNA,

00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:12.730
and there was a tiny
lightning bolt hitting it.

00:11:12.730 --> 00:11:15.540
And my teacher said,
that's how cancer happens.

00:11:15.540 --> 00:11:18.290
It's just genes getting damaged.

00:11:18.290 --> 00:11:19.010
That's it.

00:11:19.010 --> 00:11:21.540
And I remember staring
at that, staring

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:23.430
at that tiny little
lightning bolt,

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:28.740
and thinking this
is just not enough.

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:30.510
And so all of the
reading I was doing,

00:11:30.510 --> 00:11:32.980
all of the information
that I had gathered,

00:11:32.980 --> 00:11:34.870
all of the questions
I was asking

00:11:34.870 --> 00:11:37.350
that I was getting
answers to, all of it

00:11:37.350 --> 00:11:39.720
was building to
something bigger.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:44.210
At some point, I realized the
questions that I was asking

00:11:44.210 --> 00:11:48.150
were actually listed as
questions on the research goal

00:11:48.150 --> 00:11:50.760
pages for professors,
and universities,

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:53.290
and graduate labs.

00:11:53.290 --> 00:11:57.540
The same questions I was
asking as a 15-year-old

00:11:57.540 --> 00:12:01.040
were questions that the
entire scientific community

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:05.490
was asking, and
that was incredible.

00:12:05.490 --> 00:12:10.800
That was the stepping stone,
and I realized at that point

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:16.000
that I couldn't have the sort of
impact I wanted to make alone.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.510
I had to find help.

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:21.990
So in a similar way to how
you would find a restaurant

00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:25.510
to eat at tonight by searching
a few keywords on Google,

00:12:25.510 --> 00:12:27.420
I found professors.

00:12:27.420 --> 00:12:32.420
I started emailing hundreds
of professors at local labs

00:12:32.420 --> 00:12:37.630
and universities, and I
started off all of my emails

00:12:37.630 --> 00:12:42.330
with the first line saying,
hi, my name is Shree Bose.

00:12:42.330 --> 00:12:47.370
I'm 15 years old, and I
want to do cancer research.

00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:48.710
Sounds insane, right?

00:12:48.710 --> 00:12:50.720
Well, all of the
professors I e-mailed

00:12:50.720 --> 00:12:57.000
must have thought so, because
I got rejected by all of them.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.150
I mean, it got to a point
where the rejections almost

00:13:00.150 --> 00:13:01.680
didn't faze me anymore.

00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:03.920
It was almost like
my knee jerk reaction

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:06.420
to one rejection
would, OK, we're

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:08.730
on to the next professor,
the next opportunity,

00:13:08.730 --> 00:13:11.120
the next chance.

00:13:11.120 --> 00:13:14.360
I was on a mission,
and I wasn't going

00:13:14.360 --> 00:13:17.580
to stop until I found
somebody to take me on.

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:20.650
So, fully expecting
another rejection,

00:13:20.650 --> 00:13:23.430
I e-mailed Dr. Alakananda
Basu, a professor

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:26.730
at the University of North
Texas Health Science Center.

00:13:26.730 --> 00:13:30.270
Same e-mail, and
for the first time,

00:13:30.270 --> 00:13:34.430
I got a response that
wasn't, oh, you're too young,

00:13:34.430 --> 00:13:38.810
or, oh, please don't
contact me again.

00:13:38.810 --> 00:13:42.790
It was come into my
lab, and we can chat.

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:45.980
We can see why you're
excited about this,

00:13:45.980 --> 00:13:48.280
what makes you tick.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:51.820
And so I remember on
this beautiful spring

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:55.820
day in Fort Worth, Texas
I made my mom drive me

00:13:55.820 --> 00:13:57.950
to a graduate lab.

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:01.910
And I remember I was sitting
in this graduate lab.

00:14:01.910 --> 00:14:03.530
There were researchers
next to me.

00:14:03.530 --> 00:14:06.860
They're pouring buffers and
doing cool looking stuff,

00:14:06.860 --> 00:14:09.260
and that was before
I knew the science.

00:14:09.260 --> 00:14:13.010
And I remember
sitting there shaking.

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:17.060
I was physically shaking,
because all I wanted to do

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:21.060
was to work in this lab,
and I was so scared.

00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:23.430
And I remember at the time
the e-mail I was writing

00:14:23.430 --> 00:14:25.150
to all of these
professors actually

00:14:25.150 --> 00:14:29.180
had an idea for a project that
I kind of thought might work,

00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:31.210
and it was a cool idea.

00:14:31.210 --> 00:14:34.070
And Dr. Basu walks
into this lab,

00:14:34.070 --> 00:14:37.300
and one of the first things
out of her mouth is, you know,

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:41.960
I read your proposal, and
it didn't make any sense.

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:43.830
It would never work.

00:14:43.830 --> 00:14:46.885
And I remember all of
my muscles tensed up.

00:14:46.885 --> 00:14:48.990
I was like, oh god, here
comes the rejection.

00:14:48.990 --> 00:14:50.740
Here we go.

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:52.740
And then she went
on, and she said,

00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:55.440
but I like the way you
thought through it.

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:57.140
I liked where you were going.

00:14:57.140 --> 00:15:01.270
I liked the way you questioned
this entire problem,

00:15:01.270 --> 00:15:05.790
and so if you want, you can come
work in my lab for the summer,

00:15:05.790 --> 00:15:06.662
and that was it.

00:15:06.662 --> 00:15:08.490
That was where it all started.

00:15:08.490 --> 00:15:13.380
After these months of absolutely
making a fool of myself

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:17.420
and just writing nonsensical
ideas to these professors who

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:21.080
knew so much more
than me, it was really

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:27.310
that that gave me the chance
to do something amazing.

00:15:27.310 --> 00:15:29.560
So don't be afraid
to ask for help.

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:32.860
Don't be afraid to reach out
when you realize that you can't

00:15:32.860 --> 00:15:35.730
have the sort of
impact you want alone,

00:15:35.730 --> 00:15:39.100
because it's one of the most
powerful things you can do.

00:15:39.100 --> 00:15:42.130
For me, I started
working in this lab

00:15:42.130 --> 00:15:43.970
as a freshman in high school.

00:15:43.970 --> 00:15:46.240
I had just finished freshman
year of high school.

00:15:46.240 --> 00:15:48.640
I was working in this lab.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:52.000
I was assigned this project
on drug resistance in breast

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.870
cancer, so basically
understanding

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:59.270
why some cells stop
responding to a drug.

00:15:59.270 --> 00:16:05.550
And for the first summer, I
remember I just bumbled around.

00:16:05.550 --> 00:16:07.640
I broke glassware.

00:16:07.640 --> 00:16:12.430
I dropped experimental results
that took days to redo.

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:16.130
I annoyed literally
everybody in this lab

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:19.530
all the time asking
the dumbest questions,

00:16:19.530 --> 00:16:22.640
and I remember along
the way I learned.

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:26.420
I learned a lot of really,
really, really cool things,

00:16:26.420 --> 00:16:29.760
and I remember as I was
learning I kind of fell

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:31.840
in love with research.

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:33.040
It was incredible.

00:16:33.040 --> 00:16:36.290
I felt like it was
just so powerful to be

00:16:36.290 --> 00:16:39.370
able to think through a
problem and go from beginning

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:43.880
to end and have an experimental
result that could tell you

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:47.880
something about a cancer
patient who might be suffering

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:50.900
from breast cancer or a
patient who's being told

00:16:50.900 --> 00:16:53.940
that the breast
cancer has come back,

00:16:53.940 --> 00:16:56.900
and that was incredibly
powerful to me.

00:16:56.900 --> 00:16:59.430
Also, I never looked
like that in the lab.

00:16:59.430 --> 00:17:01.646
That's a very intense picture.

00:17:01.646 --> 00:17:03.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:03.890 --> 00:17:08.490
But I remember at the time
I was so excited about what

00:17:08.490 --> 00:17:12.329
I was working on, and I wanted
to share it with everybody

00:17:12.329 --> 00:17:14.560
who would listen to me.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:18.640
And I remember at the end of
the summer we had this project.

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:20.380
I had finished this
complete project.

00:17:20.380 --> 00:17:22.750
It was on drug
resistance, breast cancer,

00:17:22.750 --> 00:17:26.710
and I was ready to enter
in to another science fair.

00:17:26.710 --> 00:17:29.200
And I mean, this is a science
fair I've been competing in

00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:31.770
since I was a little
kid, and this project

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:34.790
is better than blue spinach and
remote controlled garbage cans,

00:17:34.790 --> 00:17:36.250
right?

00:17:36.250 --> 00:17:39.150
And I remember I went
to the science fair.

00:17:39.150 --> 00:17:43.240
I presented my project,
and at the awards ceremony,

00:17:43.240 --> 00:17:45.420
I won nothing.

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:49.130
I remember I walked out of this
room, and I was empty handed.

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:50.780
I was sad.

00:17:50.780 --> 00:17:55.130
I had a feeling like I never
wanted to do research again.

00:17:55.130 --> 00:17:59.180
I mean, I had fallen in love
with biology and medicine,

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:01.570
and I thought it was
the coolest thing ever.

00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:05.950
And it turned out I
kind of sucked at it,

00:18:05.950 --> 00:18:08.040
and that was dark.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:11.060
That was a crushing,
crushing sort of feeling,

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:14.550
and I remember at
the time I decided

00:18:14.550 --> 00:18:16.500
I would turn my attention
away from research.

00:18:16.500 --> 00:18:17.550
I would stop doing that.

00:18:17.550 --> 00:18:21.490
I was going to focus
on poetry and moping.

00:18:21.490 --> 00:18:23.410
Those were going to
be my two things.

00:18:23.410 --> 00:18:24.162
That was it.

00:18:24.162 --> 00:18:25.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:25.730 --> 00:18:28.430
And I kept it up for
quite a few months.

00:18:28.430 --> 00:18:33.190
I remember I felt just so
downtrodden by everything that

00:18:33.190 --> 00:18:35.670
had happened, but
after three months,

00:18:35.670 --> 00:18:38.220
I was still sitting
in biology class

00:18:38.220 --> 00:18:43.980
and still what I was learning
still was not enough.

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:48.330
And I remember the reason I had
joined a lab in the first place

00:18:48.330 --> 00:18:50.300
was because I wanted
to make a difference.

00:18:50.300 --> 00:18:52.340
I wanted to understand.

00:18:52.340 --> 00:18:55.370
I wanted to know how
this disease that

00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:58.910
had killed my grandfather
worked and how

00:18:58.910 --> 00:19:01.180
we could make it
better for everybody

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:03.220
else who was suffering.

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:05.570
And so I went back
the next year.

00:19:05.570 --> 00:19:09.390
I remember I was given
the choice-- I was given

00:19:09.390 --> 00:19:13.010
the choice to either work on
this project on breast cancer,

00:19:13.010 --> 00:19:17.826
or I could come up with a new
project on ovarian cancer,

00:19:17.826 --> 00:19:20.232
and I just jumped
at that opportunity.

00:19:20.232 --> 00:19:20.940
I was like, that.

00:19:20.940 --> 00:19:22.140
I'll do that.

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:25.070
And so over the course
of the next summer,

00:19:25.070 --> 00:19:29.560
I actually developed this really
cool project on drug resistance

00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:32.530
in ovarian cancer
along with my mentor.

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:36.120
And so basically what that meant
is we wanted to understand why

00:19:36.120 --> 00:19:40.850
some cells died when we gave
them a chemotherapy drug

00:19:40.850 --> 00:19:43.580
and why some cells didn't.

00:19:43.580 --> 00:19:46.750
And so that basically
would correlate--

00:19:46.750 --> 00:19:49.880
that would mean that we
could understand better

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:52.650
why some patients
stopped responding

00:19:52.650 --> 00:19:55.540
to some medicines--
really big stuff.

00:19:55.540 --> 00:19:58.300
And we discovered a really
cool thing-- basically

00:19:58.300 --> 00:20:00.750
that this one energy
protein that's

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:04.310
involved in how
cells process energy

00:20:04.310 --> 00:20:08.770
is actually really important
in how that switch happens.

00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:13.070
And so I remember at the time
I did this really cool project.

00:20:13.070 --> 00:20:14.950
I really wanted to
share it with the world,

00:20:14.950 --> 00:20:18.170
but it was science fairs,
and I was kind of scared.

00:20:18.170 --> 00:20:23.600
And one day, I got a call from
my dad, and my dad said, hey,

00:20:23.600 --> 00:20:26.580
have you been on the home
page of Google today?

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:28.970
There's something right
under the search bar

00:20:28.970 --> 00:20:31.160
that I think you would
be interested in.

00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:33.640
So I said, no, and
then I went online.

00:20:33.640 --> 00:20:35.400
And right under
the search bar it

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:42.250
said, introducing the first
ever Google Global Science Fair.

00:20:42.250 --> 00:20:45.750
And I thought, you know, I
wouldn't have done any of this

00:20:45.750 --> 00:20:50.010
without Google, and I want to
share what I have figured out

00:20:50.010 --> 00:20:51.530
with the world.

00:20:51.530 --> 00:20:55.160
So all of my work, all of my
passion, all of my excitement--

00:20:55.160 --> 00:20:58.350
I put that all into this
really cool website,

00:20:58.350 --> 00:21:01.680
and I sent off the link,
and a few months later, I

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:05.120
found out that I was
going to Mountain View.

00:21:05.120 --> 00:21:09.250
So I was one of 15
global finalists, which

00:21:09.250 --> 00:21:11.470
meant that, when I
went to California,

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:16.880
I was with 14 other kids
who also were doing projects

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:19.270
that could change the world.

00:21:19.270 --> 00:21:22.090
And I mean, I
remember at one point

00:21:22.090 --> 00:21:25.250
we had to have these public
booths where you brought

00:21:25.250 --> 00:21:28.240
stuff and showed it off to
the public who would come in

00:21:28.240 --> 00:21:30.217
and want to know
about your project.

00:21:30.217 --> 00:21:31.800
And they told us to
bring in something

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:33.680
that was either
representative of us

00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:36.310
or representative
of our project.

00:21:36.310 --> 00:21:39.420
And I worked with cancer,
so you can't really

00:21:39.420 --> 00:21:41.360
bring in cancer cells.

00:21:41.360 --> 00:21:45.100
So I decided, since
I'm from Texas,

00:21:45.100 --> 00:21:50.790
I would bring in a cowboy boot
and a statue of a cowboy, which

00:21:50.790 --> 00:21:52.520
is a great idea if
you think about it.

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:53.560
It's great.

00:21:53.560 --> 00:21:54.510
Only problem--

00:21:54.510 --> 00:21:55.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:55.910 --> 00:22:00.340
Only problem was that
at some point in transit

00:22:00.340 --> 00:22:03.380
the cowboy's head came off.

00:22:03.380 --> 00:22:08.280
So on my table, I had a
headless cowboy statue,

00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:13.020
and the kid next to me had a
fully functional robotic LEGO

00:22:13.020 --> 00:22:14.162
arm.

00:22:14.162 --> 00:22:16.370
And at that point, I was
like, all right, we're done.

00:22:16.370 --> 00:22:17.800
We're done here.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:19.100
We're not winning.

00:22:19.100 --> 00:22:20.570
OK, it's fine.

00:22:20.570 --> 00:22:25.040
And so I remember just knowing
that made me so much calmer.

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:29.200
So when I went in to talk
to the judges, I was honest.

00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:31.490
Mariette was one
of my judges, and I

00:22:31.490 --> 00:22:33.790
remember I was brutally honest.

00:22:33.790 --> 00:22:37.600
There were points I would
talk about messing up in lab,

00:22:37.600 --> 00:22:40.230
and getting rejected,
and why I was

00:22:40.230 --> 00:22:44.550
so excited to be able to
work on a project like this.

00:22:44.550 --> 00:22:48.080
And when I won the Google
Science Fair in 2011,

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:50.070
it didn't feel like
I was winning just

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:51.710
because of the work.

00:22:51.710 --> 00:22:56.880
It felt really like it was
an award for my passion,

00:22:56.880 --> 00:23:00.400
for how determined I
was, for how excited I

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:03.640
was to be able to work on this
thing that had affected me

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:05.230
so closely.

00:23:05.230 --> 00:23:09.840
It felt like it was really
an award for all of the kids

00:23:09.840 --> 00:23:11.590
who have ever been
told that they're

00:23:11.590 --> 00:23:15.950
too young to do something or
that-- or kids who have told

00:23:15.950 --> 00:23:20.250
themselves that they can't
do something because of age,

00:23:20.250 --> 00:23:24.120
or gender, or opportunity.

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:27.480
It was an honor to win
the Google Science Fair,

00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:30.720
and after that, I got to
do a lot of really, really

00:23:30.720 --> 00:23:36.880
cool things, including getting
to meet President Obama twice,

00:23:36.880 --> 00:23:38.910
and there was just
something about seeing

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:42.250
such a powerful person who was
so passionate about getting

00:23:42.250 --> 00:23:46.300
kids excited about science, and
technology, and engineering,

00:23:46.300 --> 00:23:48.920
and math that just
made me excited to be

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:52.520
able to share my mentorship
with the entire world.

00:23:52.520 --> 00:23:54.210
And over the past
few years, I have

00:23:54.210 --> 00:23:57.830
gotten to do a lot of
really exciting things.

00:23:57.830 --> 00:24:02.390
I mean, I've made some of
my best friends at Harvard.

00:24:02.390 --> 00:24:06.150
I started a company to
help kids get started

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:08.270
with building
technology and learning

00:24:08.270 --> 00:24:11.020
about engineering hardware.

00:24:11.020 --> 00:24:14.180
I was one of "Glamour"
magazine's top 10 college

00:24:14.180 --> 00:24:16.610
women, where they put
a lot of makeup on you

00:24:16.610 --> 00:24:18.790
and make you look a lot better.

00:24:18.790 --> 00:24:20.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:20.080 --> 00:24:23.480
I've gotten to do research
at Harvard Medical School,

00:24:23.480 --> 00:24:27.510
and I'm going on to start
my career in medicine

00:24:27.510 --> 00:24:31.680
and research, and it's been
a really, really exciting

00:24:31.680 --> 00:24:35.950
journey, but you know, I
never thought of myself

00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:42.480
as an inventor, or a
scientist, or an entrepreneur.

00:24:42.480 --> 00:24:45.850
Honestly, I just
asked the questions

00:24:45.850 --> 00:24:48.970
that mattered the most
to me, whether that

00:24:48.970 --> 00:24:54.770
was how to turn spinach
blue or how to cure cancer.

00:24:54.770 --> 00:24:58.780
And so today I want you
to do something with me.

00:24:58.780 --> 00:25:03.060
I want you to think about the
problems that matter to you.

00:25:03.060 --> 00:25:05.700
The world is this
giant beautiful place,

00:25:05.700 --> 00:25:09.969
and there's so much left
to explore and discover.

00:25:09.969 --> 00:25:11.510
So let's think about
it for a second.

00:25:11.510 --> 00:25:14.720
What are those questions
that matter to you?

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:18.240
And now I want you to go
do something with that,

00:25:18.240 --> 00:25:21.480
because that's where
everything I have done so far

00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:24.400
has begun-- with a question.

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:27.630
And that's where I want your
stories and your journeys

00:25:27.630 --> 00:25:29.640
to begin, as well.

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:34.280
So today I want you to
find your questions,

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:38.800
make your opportunities,
and create your own answers,

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:41.090
because together
I know we can do

00:25:41.090 --> 00:25:46.670
incredible things in this world
if we only begin to ask, how?

00:25:49.436 --> 00:25:50.360
[APPLAUSE]

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:51.180
Thank you, guys.

00:26:00.430 --> 00:26:03.400
So you guys did a really great
job with asking questions,

00:26:03.400 --> 00:26:05.660
so I'm going to go
to these questions.

00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:07.502
Oh, we've got a lot.

00:26:07.502 --> 00:26:08.960
MARIETTE DICHRISTINA:
Yeah, you do.

00:26:08.960 --> 00:26:11.340
SHREE BOSE: Yes.

00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:14.830
Let's go with the top
voted one from Leila,

00:26:14.830 --> 00:26:17.610
who asks, making the
world better sounds hard.

00:26:17.610 --> 00:26:19.300
How do I even start?

00:26:19.300 --> 00:26:22.160
And I love this question,
because it's not something

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:23.430
you really think about.

00:26:23.430 --> 00:26:25.850
You don't start off
by saying, well,

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:27.110
I want to change the world.

00:26:27.110 --> 00:26:30.440
You start off by saying this
is something that bothers me,

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:32.870
and I want to figure
it out, and then

00:26:32.870 --> 00:26:35.900
you find out that this thing
that bothered you actually

00:26:35.900 --> 00:26:39.540
bothers a lot of people
that's how it all starts.

00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:42.490
So you asked, how
do you even start?

00:26:42.490 --> 00:26:43.660
Good question.

00:26:43.660 --> 00:26:46.540
I want all of us
to take one second

00:26:46.540 --> 00:26:48.420
and think about a
problem that you've

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:51.786
run into today-- just today.

00:26:51.786 --> 00:26:53.160
Maybe it's not
even your problem.

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:55.320
Maybe it's a problem that
your parents ran into,

00:26:55.320 --> 00:26:57.530
or a friend, or somebody
else, but let's think

00:26:57.530 --> 00:27:00.580
of that problem.

00:27:00.580 --> 00:27:03.520
Got it?

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:08.470
Now I want you to think
about how you would solve it.

00:27:08.470 --> 00:27:12.040
Is there an easy way to do that?

00:27:12.040 --> 00:27:13.350
We'll start with that.

00:27:13.350 --> 00:27:15.340
That's how you start
changing the world.

00:27:15.340 --> 00:27:17.490
That's how everything
begins-- is really

00:27:17.490 --> 00:27:20.900
finding a problem
that impacts you

00:27:20.900 --> 00:27:23.970
and then trying to come up
with solutions that can matter

00:27:23.970 --> 00:27:27.420
to everyone, but that's
a really great question,

00:27:27.420 --> 00:27:30.680
and thank you, Leila.

00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:34.700
So, second question
is, what was it

00:27:34.700 --> 00:27:36.720
like to meet President Obama?

00:27:36.720 --> 00:27:40.600
Oh, I was so starstruck.

00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:41.590
I remember this.

00:27:41.590 --> 00:27:42.750
I was so starstruck.

00:27:42.750 --> 00:27:46.090
They had us in this little
waiting area outside the Oval

00:27:46.090 --> 00:27:48.910
Office at the very beginning,
and the Oval Office

00:27:48.910 --> 00:27:50.590
has a lot of hidden doors.

00:27:50.590 --> 00:27:54.380
So there's no really
blatant doors anywhere,

00:27:54.380 --> 00:27:55.840
and so I remember
I was standing.

00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:57.920
I was facing somebody
else talking,

00:27:57.920 --> 00:28:00.380
and there was a wall behind
me, and I turned around,

00:28:00.380 --> 00:28:02.300
and all of a sudden
the wall was gone.

00:28:02.300 --> 00:28:05.560
It was a door, and President
Obama is standing there,

00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:08.020
and he goes in
for the handshake.

00:28:08.020 --> 00:28:10.440
And I'm so panicked
at that point

00:28:10.440 --> 00:28:11.880
that I just bear hugged him.

00:28:11.880 --> 00:28:14.742
[APPLAUSE]

00:28:14.742 --> 00:28:18.100
So it was amazing to
meet President Obama,

00:28:18.100 --> 00:28:23.330
but absolutely honestly it
was incredible to really see

00:28:23.330 --> 00:28:25.950
somebody who is in such
a high position who

00:28:25.950 --> 00:28:29.670
very evidently cared so much
about getting kids started

00:28:29.670 --> 00:28:30.790
in science.

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:33.130
That's a really
powerful thing, and I

00:28:33.130 --> 00:28:36.820
think it sets a tone for how we
approach STEM in this country,

00:28:36.820 --> 00:28:39.530
and that's incredible, and
that's something all of us

00:28:39.530 --> 00:28:42.890
will benefit from.

00:28:42.890 --> 00:28:45.790
Thank you, Steven, for
that wonderful question

00:28:45.790 --> 00:28:49.700
where I got to share
my bear hug with Obama.

00:28:49.700 --> 00:28:51.490
Our next question is from Dre.

00:28:51.490 --> 00:28:53.800
How can we bridge
the gap with the lack

00:28:53.800 --> 00:28:56.450
of women of color in
science and STEM--

00:28:56.450 --> 00:28:59.710
so science, technology,
engineering, and math--

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:02.230
and that is a really,
really good question

00:29:02.230 --> 00:29:06.300
because that's something I'm
especially passionate about.

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:08.320
I mean, I grew-- I
was really lucky.

00:29:08.320 --> 00:29:11.490
I grew up in a household
where it didn't really

00:29:11.490 --> 00:29:13.610
feel like I couldn't
do something.

00:29:13.610 --> 00:29:15.410
That really wasn't a big thing.

00:29:15.410 --> 00:29:17.190
So when I wanted
to start research,

00:29:17.190 --> 00:29:20.750
it didn't feel like there were
any barriers to making that

00:29:20.750 --> 00:29:25.750
happen, and so actually when
I was first starting this tech

00:29:25.750 --> 00:29:29.690
company with my co-founder,
who happens to be a man,

00:29:29.690 --> 00:29:31.930
we ended up going to
this tech conference.

00:29:31.930 --> 00:29:36.010
And our boxes actually look
like they're made out of wood,

00:29:36.010 --> 00:29:39.360
so they look kind of
just like regular boxes

00:29:39.360 --> 00:29:41.860
that you might carry
snacks around in.

00:29:41.860 --> 00:29:46.480
And this tech conference was
full-- it mostly-- 80% men.

00:29:46.480 --> 00:29:48.470
And I remember we
were walking around,

00:29:48.470 --> 00:29:50.750
and I was holding
the box, and I got

00:29:50.750 --> 00:29:56.820
asked three times if there
were cookies in the box.

00:29:56.820 --> 00:29:59.210
And after the third time,
I was like, this is weird.

00:29:59.210 --> 00:30:00.340
This is definitely weird.

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:02.860
So I handed it off
to my co-founder,

00:30:02.860 --> 00:30:05.240
and for the next hour,
he carried it around.

00:30:05.240 --> 00:30:08.090
The questions he got were,
what cool piece of tech

00:30:08.090 --> 00:30:08.946
is in that box?

00:30:12.390 --> 00:30:15.870
It's really hard to say that
these gender divides don't

00:30:15.870 --> 00:30:17.950
still exist, and they do.

00:30:17.950 --> 00:30:20.540
And I think one of the
most powerful things we

00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:24.030
can do to bridge that gap
that you're talking about here

00:30:24.030 --> 00:30:26.020
is actually better mentoring.

00:30:26.020 --> 00:30:28.150
I think that's
the key to letting

00:30:28.150 --> 00:30:31.820
amazing thoughts and amazing
people come to the forefront

00:30:31.820 --> 00:30:35.300
and giving them the chance to
really do what they want to do.

00:30:35.300 --> 00:30:37.310
My entire journey
started with mentoring,

00:30:37.310 --> 00:30:40.810
and I think it's a
very powerful thing.

00:30:40.810 --> 00:30:41.710
So thank you, Dre.

00:30:45.420 --> 00:30:53.080
My next question is
from Steve, who asks,

00:30:53.080 --> 00:30:56.360
how did you figure out how to
get started with your cancer

00:30:56.360 --> 00:30:57.380
research?

00:30:57.380 --> 00:30:59.630
And this is an awesome
question, because honestly I

00:30:59.630 --> 00:31:02.640
didn't have a plotted
out way to do things.

00:31:02.640 --> 00:31:05.870
I started reading and
reading everything

00:31:05.870 --> 00:31:10.040
I possibly could, and then just
proposing nonsensical ideas

00:31:10.040 --> 00:31:12.000
to people who knew
a lot more than me,

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:15.406
but I would say the
first step to my journey

00:31:15.406 --> 00:31:17.030
on getting started
with cancer research

00:31:17.030 --> 00:31:18.760
was by finding a mentor.

00:31:18.760 --> 00:31:21.000
And so for a lot of you
students out in the audience,

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:23.400
and even actually for
parents and Googlers,

00:31:23.400 --> 00:31:25.314
I think one of the most
powerful things you

00:31:25.314 --> 00:31:27.730
can do when you want to change
something or make something

00:31:27.730 --> 00:31:31.560
better is to find the
people who can help you

00:31:31.560 --> 00:31:34.600
and to not be afraid to
reach out to those people,

00:31:34.600 --> 00:31:36.890
make a fool of yourself
if you have to,

00:31:36.890 --> 00:31:40.470
but eventually that's
what makes the difference.

00:31:40.470 --> 00:31:41.620
That is it.

00:31:41.620 --> 00:31:44.757
Going out and doing something
is the very first step,

00:31:44.757 --> 00:31:46.590
whether that's reading
and then figuring out

00:31:46.590 --> 00:31:50.290
that you need to find mentors
or just reaching out and talking

00:31:50.290 --> 00:31:52.719
to people who might
be able to help you.

00:31:52.719 --> 00:31:53.760
So really great question.

00:31:53.760 --> 00:31:54.526
Thank you, Steve.

