I love this question.

00:34:36.280 --> 00:34:39.130
What was your most
inspiring learning memory

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:41.409
in school and outside of school?

00:34:41.409 --> 00:34:42.860
So this is from Jonathan.

00:34:42.860 --> 00:34:45.139
Thank you, Jonathan.

00:34:45.139 --> 00:34:50.159
I think in school one of my
most inspiring learning moments

00:34:50.159 --> 00:34:53.920
was actually with
my biology teacher.

00:34:53.920 --> 00:34:56.020
At one point, when I
wasn't understanding

00:34:56.020 --> 00:34:58.590
what was happening in class, I
went in, and I talked to her,

00:34:58.590 --> 00:35:01.490
and I said, you know,
this doesn't make sense.

00:35:01.490 --> 00:35:03.010
And she was one of
the first people

00:35:03.010 --> 00:35:05.510
who said, if this
doesn't make sense,

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:08.140
try to find some
higher level things.

00:35:08.140 --> 00:35:11.410
And I remember at the time
the things I was reading

00:35:11.410 --> 00:35:12.770
didn't really make sense.

00:35:12.770 --> 00:35:16.560
The scientific articles
were full of jargon.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:21.360
So I went from having to
Google every other word,

00:35:21.360 --> 00:35:24.690
and as I read more, I would
have to Google every fifth word.

00:35:24.690 --> 00:35:26.900
And that was
progress, but that was

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:28.360
one of my most
inspiring moments--

00:35:28.360 --> 00:35:31.230
was this teacher
really telling me,

00:35:31.230 --> 00:35:34.830
you know, learn outside
of just this classroom.

00:35:34.830 --> 00:35:38.540
Learn as much as you possibly
can and use all of the tools

00:35:38.540 --> 00:35:44.280
you have to figure out what
information you want to get.

00:35:44.280 --> 00:35:48.370
Outside of school, actually,
is one of my earliest memories

00:35:48.370 --> 00:35:52.160
with science that
actually solidified why

00:35:52.160 --> 00:35:54.810
I was excited about science.

00:35:54.810 --> 00:35:56.510
I grew up with an older brother.

00:35:56.510 --> 00:35:59.450
He's two years older
than me, super cool.

00:35:59.450 --> 00:36:01.390
And when we were
little, I remember

00:36:01.390 --> 00:36:05.300
he would come home
every day, and since I

00:36:05.300 --> 00:36:08.780
was younger and the only
person he could boss around,

00:36:08.780 --> 00:36:12.040
he would make me sit down, and
he would explain everything

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:14.030
he learned in science class.

00:36:14.030 --> 00:36:16.930
And I remember he had
this spark in his eye,

00:36:16.930 --> 00:36:20.810
and there was just something
magical about being taught

00:36:20.810 --> 00:36:25.480
by somebody who is so obviously
excited about what he is saying

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:29.430
that just I remember
looking at him and thinking,

00:36:29.430 --> 00:36:31.090
I want to be that excited.

00:36:31.090 --> 00:36:34.170
I want to be that excited
about atoms, and molecules,

00:36:34.170 --> 00:36:36.640
and cells, and things that
I didn't even understand,

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:41.480
but let us break apart the world
and put it back together again.

00:36:41.480 --> 00:36:43.130
And so I think that
was one of my most

00:36:43.130 --> 00:36:46.190
inspiring just general
memories in life--

00:36:46.190 --> 00:36:48.840
has been the influence
of my older brother

00:36:48.840 --> 00:36:52.230
and having him teach
me, and still teach me

00:36:52.230 --> 00:36:54.919
throughout my entire life.

